<div class='commentinfo comment_comment'>
2011-04-22 03:38:37 (1135 days ago)
<div id='contact-7417'><span class='name'>Robert Farmer</span><span class='send-message'><a href="/content/Contact/view/contactid/7417/display/detail/">Details</a></span></div> </div>
<div class='commentbox'>
I don't know why anyone would say that this is a &quot;safe&quot; place to paddle. The hydraulics, although<br/>
they can be trivial at low levels, are potentially deadly at higher levels. It all depends on the<br/>
level, and knowing the differences requires experience. As my biochemistry teacher likes to say,<br/>
&quot;The dose makes the poison,&quot; meaning that a little of almost anything, like water, might be safe,<br/>
but a lot of something, especially water, can still kill you. For example, the Russell Fork is<br/>
great fun at 150 cfs, but should you be there at 1500+? Safe to say, &quot;No!&quot; </div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
